{"text": "In a historical experiment to determine Planck's constant, a metal surface was irradiated with light of different wavelengths. The emitted photoelectron energies were measured by applying a stopping potential. The relevant data for the wavelength ($\lambda$) and the corresponding stopping potential ($V_0$) are given below:

$$\begin{array}{|c|c|} \hline \lambda (\mu\text{m}) & V_0 (\text{Volt}) \\ \hline 0.3 & 2.0 \\ \hline 0.4 & 1.0 \\ \hline 0.5 & 0.4 \\ \hline \end{array}$$

Given that $c = 3 \times 10^8 \text{ ms}^{-1}$ and $e = 1.6 \times 10^{-19} \text{ C}$, Planck's constant (in units of J-s) found from such an experiment is:", "image_url": ""}

{"text": "The major product of the following reaction sequence is:

$$\text{}$$

Choose the correct option from the following:", "image_url": "https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/d/1VAFMBNVdLfgXf1n0WSFK-kW-RS_85R3v=w1200"}

{"text": "A charged particle (electron or proton) is introduced at the origin $(x = 0, y = 0, z = 0)$ with a given initial velocity $\vec{v}$. A uniform electric field $\vec{E}$ and magnetic field $\vec{B}$ are given in columns 1, 2 and 3, respectively. The quantities $E_0, B_0$ are positive in magnitude.

$$\begin{array}{|l|l|l|} \hline \textbf{Column I} & \textbf{Column 2} & \textbf{Column 3} \\ \hline (\text{I}) \text{ Electron with } \vec{v} = 2\frac{E_0}{B_0}\hat{x} & (i) \vec{E} = E_0 \hat{z} & (P) \vec{B} = -B_0 \hat{x} \\ \hline (\text{II}) \text{ Electron with } \vec{v} = \frac{E_0}{B_0}\hat{y} & (ii) \vec{E} = -E_0 \hat{y} & (Q) \vec{B} = B_0 \hat{x} \\ \hline (\text{III}) \text{ Proton with } \vec{v} = 0 & (iii) \vec{E} = -E_0 \hat{x} & (R) \vec{B} = B_0 \hat{y} \\ \hline (\text{IV}) \text{ Proton with } \vec{v} = 2\frac{E_0}{B_0}\hat{x} & (iv) \vec{E} = E_0 \hat{x} & (S) \vec{B} = B_0 \hat{z} \\ \hline \end{array}$$

In which case would the particle move in a straight line along the negative direction of $y$-axis (i.e., move along $-\hat{y}$)?", "image_url": ""}

{"text": "A charged particle (electron or proton) is introduced at the origin $(x = 0, y = 0, z = 0)$ with a given initial velocity $\vec{v}$. A uniform electric field $\vec{E}$ and magnetic field $\vec{B}$ are given in columns 1, 2 and 3, respectively. The quantities $E_0, B_0$ are positive in magnitude.

$$\begin{array}{|l|l|l|} \hline \textbf{Column I} & \textbf{Column 2} & \textbf{Column 3} \\ \hline (\text{I}) \text{ Electron with } \vec{v} = 2\frac{E_0}{B_0}\hat{x} & (i) \vec{E} = E_0 \hat{z} & (P) \vec{B} = -B_0 \hat{x} \\ \hline (\text{II}) \text{ Electron with } \vec{v} = \frac{E_0}{B_0}\hat{y} & (ii) \vec{E} = -E_0 \hat{y} & (Q) \vec{B} = B_0 \hat{x} \\ \hline (\text{III}) \text{ Proton with } \vec{v} = 0 & (iii) \vec{E} = -E_0 \hat{x} & (R) \vec{B} = B_0 \hat{y} \\ \hline (\text{IV}) \text{ Proton with } \vec{v} = 2\frac{E_0}{B_0}\hat{x} & (iv) \vec{E} = E_0 \hat{x} & (S) \vec{B} = B_0 \hat{z} \\ \hline \end{array}$$
In which case will the particle move in a straight line with constant velocity?", "image_url": ""}

{"text": "An organic acid $\text{P}$ $(\text{C}_{11}\text{H}_{12}\text{O}_2)$ can easily be oxidized to a dibasic acid which reacts with ethylene glycol to produce a polymer Dacron. Upon ozonolysis, $\text{P}$ gives an aliphatic ketone as one of the products. $\text{P}$ undergoes the following reaction sequences to furnish $\text{R}$ via $\text{Q}$. The compound $\text{P}$ also undergoes another set of reactions to produce $\text{S}$.

$$\text{S} \xleftarrow[\text{5) } \text{H}_2/\text{Pd-C}]{\begin{matrix} \text{1) } \text{H}_2/\text{Pd-C} \\ \text{2) } \text{NH}_3/\Delta \\ \text{3) } \text{Br}_2/\text{NaOH} \\ \text{4) } \text{CHCl}_3, \text{ KOH}, \Delta \end{matrix}} \text{P} \xrightarrow[\text{4) } \text{NaBH}_4]{\begin{matrix} \text{1) } \text{H}_2/\text{Pd-C} \\ \text{2) } \text{SOCl}_2 \\ \text{3) } \text{MeMgBr, } \text{CdCl}_2 \end{matrix}} \text{Q} \xrightarrow[\text{4) } \text{H}_3\text{O}^+]{\begin{matrix} \text{1) } \text{HCl} \\ \text{2) } \text{Mg/Et}_2\text{O} \\ \text{3) } \text{CO}_2 \text{ (dry ice)} \end{matrix}} \text{R}$$

The compound $\text{S}$ is:", "image_url": ""}

{"text": "An organic acid $\text{P}$ $(\text{C}_{11}\text{H}_{12}\text{O}_2)$ can easily be oxidized to a dibasic acid which reacts with ethylene glycol to produce a polymer Dacron. Upon ozonolysis, $\text{P}$ gives an aliphatic ketone as one of the products. $\text{P}$ undergoes the following reaction sequences to furnish $\text{R}$ via $\text{Q}$. The compound $\text{P}$ also undergoes another set of reactions to produce $\text{S}$.

$$\text{S} \xleftarrow[\text{5) } \text{H}_2/\text{Pd-C}]{\begin{matrix} \text{1) } \text{H}_2/\text{Pd-C} \\ \text{2) } \text{NH}_3/\Delta \\ \text{3) } \text{Br}_2/\text{NaOH} \\ \text{4) } \text{CHCl}_3, \text{ KOH}, \Delta \end{matrix}} \text{P} \xrightarrow[\text{4) } \text{NaBH}_4]{\begin{matrix} \text{1) } \text{H}_2/\text{Pd-C} \\ \text{2) } \text{SOCl}_2 \\ \text{3) } \text{MeMgBr, } \text{CdCl}_2 \end{matrix}} \text{Q} \xrightarrow[\text{4) } \text{H}_3\text{O}^+]{\begin{matrix} \text{1) } \text{HCl} \\ \text{2) } \text{Mg/Et}_2\text{O} \\ \text{3) } \text{CO}_2 \text{ (dry ice)} \end{matrix}} \text{R}$$

The compound $\text{R}$ is:", "image_url": ""}

{"text": "For a reaction, $\text{A} \rightleftharpoons \text{P}$, the plots of [A] and [P] with time at temperatures $T_1$ and $T_2$ are given below.

 and [P] at $T_1$ and $T_2$]

If $T_2 > T_1$, the correct statement(s) is (are) (Assume $\Delta H^\ominus$ and $\Delta S^\ominus$ are independent of temperature and ratio of $\ln K$ at $T_1$ to $\ln K$ at $T_2$ is greater than $T_2/T_1$. Here $H, S, G$ and $K$ are enthalpy, entropy, Gibbs energy and equilibrium constant, respectively.)", "image_url": "https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/d/1d13XhJmGOsccmRQm-FICMzy6wjZjwpKV=w1200"}

{"text": "Define the collections $\{E_1, E_2, E_3, ...\}$ of ellipses and $\{R_1, R_2, R_3...\}$ of rectangles as follows :
$E_1: \frac{x^2}{9} + \frac{y^2}{4} = 1$;
$R_1$ : rectangle of largest area, with sides parallel to the axes, inscribed in $E_1$;
$E_n$ : ellipse $\frac{x^2}{a_n^2} + \frac{y^2}{b_n^2} = 1$ of the largest area inscribed in $R_{n-1}, n > 1$;
$R_n$ : rectangle of largest area, with sides parallel to the axes, inscribed in $E_n, n > 1$.
Then which of the following options is/are correct?", "image_url": ""}

{"text": "Let $f : \mathbb{R} \to \mathbb{R}$ be given by
\[ f(x) = \left\{ \begin{array}{ll}
x^5 + 5x^4 + 10x^3 + 10x^2 + 3x + 1, & x < 0; \\
x^2 - x + 1, & 0 \le x < 1; \\
\frac{2}{3}x^3 - 4x^2 + 7x - \frac{8}{3}, & 1 \le x < 3; \\
(x - 2)\log_e(x - 2) - x + \frac{10}{3}, & x \ge 3;
\end{array} \right. \]
Then which of the following options is/are correct?", "image_url": ""}

{"text": "Consider the following reactions (unbalanced).
$$Zn + \text{Hot conc. } H_2SO_4 \mathrel{\mathop{\kern0pt\longrightarrow}
\limits_{}} G + R + X$$
$$Zn + \text{conc. } NaOH \mathrel{\mathop{\kern0pt\longrightarrow}
\limits_{}} T + Q$$
$$G + H_2S + NH_4OH \mathrel{\mathop{\kern0pt\longrightarrow}
\limits_{}} Z \,(\text{a precipitate}) + X + Y$$
Choose the correct option(s).", "image_url": ""}

{"text": "In a thermodynamic process on an ideal monatomic gas, the infinitesimal heat absorbed by the gas is given by $T dX$, where $T$ is temperature and $dX$ is the infinitesimal change in a thermodynamic quantity $X$. For a mole of monatomic ideal gas $X = \frac{3}{2} R \ln\left(\frac{T}{T_A}\right) + R \ln\left(\frac{V}{V_A}\right)$, where $R$ is the gas constant, $V$ is volume, and $T_A, V_A$ are constants. The process is carried out as shown in the $PV$-diagram with $P_0V_0 = \frac{1}{3} RT_0$. Match List-I with List-II:

$$\begin{array}{|l|l|l|l|} \hline \pmb{\text{List-I}} & & \pmb{\text{List-II}} & \\ \hline \text{(I)} & \text{Work done by the system in } 1 \to 2 \to 3 & \text{(P)} & \frac{1}{3} RT_0 \ln 2 \\ \hline \text{(II)} & \text{Change in internal energy in } 1 \to 2 \to 3 & \text{(Q)} & \frac{1}{3} RT_0 \\ \hline \text{(III)} & \text{Heat absorbed by the system in } 1 \to 2 \to 3 & \text{(R)} & RT_0 \\ \hline \text{(IV)} & \text{Heat absorbed by the system in } 1 \to 2 & \text{(S)} & \frac{4}{3} RT_0 \\ \hline & & \text{(T)} & \frac{1}{3} RT_0 (3 + \ln 2) \\ \hline & & \text{(U)} & \frac{5}{6} RT_0 \\ \hline \end{array}$$

If the process on one mole of monatomic ideal gas is as shown in the TV-diagram with $P_0V_0 = \frac{1}{3} RT_0$, the correct match for the quantities in List-I and List-II is:", "image_url": "https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/d/1jSWKDW38ALjJvaKV-qL27YfNK2e0t9bs=w1200"}

{"text": "A musical instrument is made using four different metal strings: 1, 2, 3 and 4 with mass per unit length $\mu, 2\mu, 3\mu$ and $4\mu$ respectively. The instrument is played by vibrating the strings by varying the free length in the range $L_0$ to $2L_0$. It is found that for string-1 with mass per unit length $\mu$, free length $L_0$ and tension $T_0$, the fundamental mode frequency is $f_0$. 

If the tension in each string is $T_0$, identify the correct match for the highest fundamental frequency (in $f_0$ units) for each string.

$$\begin{array}{|l|l|} \hline \textbf{List-I (Strings)} & \textbf{List-II (Highest Fundamental Frequency)} \\ \hline \text{I. String 1} & \text{P. } f_0 \\ \text{II. String 2} & \text{Q. } f_0/2 \\ \text{III. String 3} & \text{R. } f_0/\sqrt{2} \\ \text{IV. String 4} & \text{S. } f_0/\sqrt{3} \\ & \text{T. } f_0/\sqrt{6} \\ \hline \end{array}$$", "image_url": ""}

{"text": "In a thermodynamic process on an ideal monatomic gas, the infinitesimal heat absorbed by the gas is given by $T dX$, where $T$ is temperature and $dX$ is the infinitesimal change in a thermodynamic quantity $X$. For a mole of monatomic ideal gas $X = \frac{3}{2} R \ln\left(\frac{T}{T_A}\right) + R \ln\left(\frac{V}{V_A}\right)$, where $R$ is the gas constant, $V$ is volume, and $T_A, V_A$ are constants. The process is carried out as shown in the $PV$-diagram with $P_0V_0 = \frac{1}{3} RT_0$. Match List-I with List-II:

$$\begin{array}{|l|l|l|l|} \hline \pmb{\text{List-I}} & & \pmb{\text{List-II}} & \\ \hline \text{(I)} & \text{Work done by the system in } 1 \to 2 \to 3 & \text{(P)} & \frac{1}{3} RT_0 \ln 2 \\ \hline \text{(II)} & \text{Change in internal energy in } 1 \to 2 \to 3 & \text{(Q)} & \frac{1}{3} RT_0 \\ \hline \text{(III)} & \text{Heat absorbed by the system in } 1 \to 2 \to 3 & \text{(R)} & RT_0 \\ \hline \text{(IV)} & \text{Heat absorbed by the system in } 1 \to 2 & \text{(S)} & \frac{4}{3} RT_0 \\ \hline & & \text{(T)} & \frac{1}{3} RT_0 (3 + \ln 2) \\ \hline & & \text{(U)} & \frac{5}{6} RT_0 \\ \hline \end{array}$$

Choose the correct match:", "image_url": "https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/d/12toe16FP2CY4siNLuXVbdwLo7eIefy9w=w1200"}

{"text": "Consider the Bohr's model of a one-electron atom where the electron moves around the nucleus. In the following, List-I contains some quantities for the $n^{\text{th}}$ orbit of the atom and List-II contains options showing how they depend on $n$.

$$\begin{array}{|l|l|l|l|} \hline \pmb{\text{LIST-I}} & & \pmb{\text{LIST-II}} & \\ \hline \text{(I)} & \text{Radius of the } n^{\text{th}} \text{ orbit} & \text{(P)} & \propto n^{-2} \\ \hline \text{(II)} & \text{Angular momentum of the electron in the } n^{\text{th}} \text{ orbit} & \text{(Q)} & \propto n^{-1} \\ \hline \text{(III)} & \text{Kinetic energy of the electron in the } n^{\text{th}} \text{ orbit} & \text{(R)} & \propto n^0 \\ \hline \text{(IV)} & \text{Potential energy of the electron in the } n^{\text{th}} \text{ orbit} & \text{(S)} & \propto n^1 \\ \hline & & \text{(T)} & \propto n^2 \\ \hline & & \text{(U)} & \propto n^{1/2} \\ \hline \end{array}$$

Which of the following options has the correct combination considering List-I and List-II?", "image_url": ""}

{"text": "Consider the Bohr's model of a one-electron atom where the electron moves around the nucleus. In the following, List-I contains some quantities for the $n^{\text{th}}$ orbit of the atom and List-II contains options showing how they depend on $n$.

$$\begin{array}{|l|l|l|l|} \hline \pmb{\text{LIST-I}} & & \pmb{\text{LIST-II}} & \\ \hline \text{(I)} & \text{Radius of the } n^{\text{th}} \text{ orbit} & \text{(P)} & \propto n^{-2} \\ \hline \text{(II)} & \text{Angular momentum of the electron in the } n^{\text{th}} \text{ orbit} & \text{(Q)} & \propto n^{-1} \\ \hline \text{(III)} & \text{Kinetic energy of the electron in the } n^{\text{th}} \text{ orbit} & \text{(R)} & \propto n^0 \\ \hline \text{(IV)} & \text{Potential energy of the electron in the } n^{\text{th}} \text{ orbit} & \text{(S)} & \propto n^1 \\ \hline & & \text{(T)} & \propto n^2 \\ \hline & & \text{(U)} & \propto n^{1/2} \\ \hline \end{array}$$

Which of the following options has the correct combination considering List-I and List-II?", "image_url": ""}

{"text": "For any $3 \times 3$ array $M$, let $|M|$ denote the determinant of $M$. Let
$$
E = \begin{array}{ccc} 1 & 2 & 3 \\ 2 & 3 & 4 \\ 8 & 13 & 18 \end{array}, \quad P = \begin{array}{ccc} 1 & 0 & 0 \\ 0 & 0 & 1 \\ 0 & 1 & 0 \end{array} \text{ and } F = \begin{array}{ccc} 1 & 3 & 2 \\ 8 & 18 & 13 \\ 2 & 4 & 3 \end{array}
$$
If $Q$ is a nonsingular array of order $3 \times 3$, then which of the following statements is(are) TRUE?", "image_url": ""}

{"text": "Considering only the principal values of the inverse trigonometric functions, the value of
$$
\frac{3}{2} \cos ^{-1} \sqrt{\frac{2}{2+\pi^{2}}}+\frac{1}{4} \sin ^{-1} \frac{2 \sqrt{2} \pi}{2+\pi^{2}}+\tan ^{-1} \frac{\sqrt{2}}{\pi}
$$
is", "image_url": ""}

{"text": "Let $P_{1}$ and $P_{2}$ be two planes given by
$$
\begin{aligned}
&P_{1}: 10 x+15 y+12 z-60=0 \\
&P_{2}:-2 x+5 y+4 z-20=0
\end{aligned}
$$
Which of the following straight lines can be an edge of some tetrahedron whose two faces lie on $P_{1}$ and $P_{2}$ ?", "image_url": ""}

{"text": "Let $z$ be a complex number with a non-zero imaginary part. If
$$
\frac{2+3z+4z^{2}}{2-3z+4z^{2}}
$$
is a real number, then the value of $|z|^{2}$ is _________.", "image_url": ""}

{"text": "Let $\beta$ be a real number. Consider the matrix
$$
A=\begin{pmatrix}
\beta & 0 & 1 \\
2 & 1 & -2 \\
3 & 1 & -2
\end{pmatrix}
$$
If $A^7 - (\beta - 1)A^6 - \beta A^5$ is a singular matrix, then the value of $9\beta$ is _________.", "image_url": ""}

{"text": "Let $\alpha$ and $\beta$ be real numbers such that $-\frac{\pi}{4}<\beta<0<\alpha<\frac{\pi}{4}$. If $\sin (\alpha+\beta)=\frac{1}{3}$ and $\cos (\alpha-\beta)=\frac{2}{3}$, then the greatest integer less than or equal to
$$
\left(\frac{\sin \alpha}{\cos \beta}+\frac{\cos \beta}{\sin \alpha}+\frac{\cos \alpha}{\sin \beta}+\frac{\sin \beta}{\cos \alpha}\right)^{2}
$$
is", "image_url": ""}

{"text": "Let $\hat{\imath}, \hat{\jmath}$ and $\hat{k}$ be the unit vectors along the three positive coordinate axes. Let
\[
\begin{aligned}
& \vec{a}=3 \hat{\imath}+\hat{\jmath}-\hat{k} \text {, } \\
& \vec{b}=\hat{\imath}+b_{2} \hat{\jmath}+b_{3} \hat{k}, \quad b_{2}, b_{3} \in \mathbb{R} \text {, } \\
& \vec{c}=c_{1} \hat{\imath}+c_{2} \hat{\jmath}+c_{3} \hat{k}, \quad c_{1}, c_{2}, c_{3} \in \mathbb{R}
\end{aligned}
\]
be three vectors such that $b_{2} b_{3}>0$, $\vec{a} \cdot \vec{b}=0$ and
\[
\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
0 & -c_{3} & c_{2} \\
c_{3} & 0 & -c_{1} \\
-c_{2} & c_{1} & 0
\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{l}
1 \\
b_{2} \\
b_{3}
\end{array}\right)=\left(\begin{array}{r}
3-c_{1} \\
1-c_{2} \\
-1-c_{3}
\end{array}\right) .
\]
Then, which of the following is/are TRUE?", "image_url": ""}

{"text": "Let $\bar{z}$ denote the complex conjugate of a complex number $z$. If $z$ is a non-zero complex number for which both real and imaginary parts of
$$
(\bar{z})^{2}+\frac{1}{z^{2}}
$$
are integers, then which of the following is/are possible value(s) of $|z|$ ?", "image_url": ""}

{"text": "The major products obtained from the reactions in List-II are the reactants for the named reactions mentioned in List-I. Match List-I with List-II and choose the correct option.

$\begin{array}{|l|l|} \hline \textbf{List-I} & \textbf{List-II} \\ \hline (P) \text{ Etard reaction} & (1) \text{ Acetophenone } \xrightarrow{\text{Zn-Hg, HCl}} \\ \hline (Q) \text{ Gattermann reaction} & (2) \text{ Toluene } \xrightarrow[\text{(ii) SOCl}_2]{\text{(i) KMnO}_4, \text{ KOH, } \Delta} \\ \hline (R) \text{ Gattermann-Koch reaction} & (3) \text{ Benzene } \xrightarrow{\text{CH}_3\text{Cl, anhyd. AlCl}_3} \\ \hline (S) \text{ Rosenmund reduction} & (4) \text{ Aniline } \xrightarrow[273-278 \text{ K}]{\text{NaNO}_2 / \text{HCl}} \\ \hline & (5) \text{ Phenol } \xrightarrow{\text{Zn, } \Delta} \\ \hline \end{array}$
", "image_url": ""}

{"text": "Let \( n \geq 2 \) be a natural number and \( f:[0,1] \rightarrow \mathbb{R} \) be the function defined by
\[
f(x)= \begin{cases}n(1-2 n x) & \text{if } 0 \leq x \leq \frac{1}{2 n} \\ 2 n(2 n x-1) & \text{if } \frac{1}{2 n} \leq x \leq \frac{3}{4 n} \\ 4 n(1-n x) & \text{if } \frac{3}{4 n} \leq x \leq \frac{1}{n} \\ \frac{n}{n-1}(n x-1) & \text{if } \frac{1}{n} \leq x \leq 1\end{cases}
\]
If \( n \) is such that the area of the region bounded by the curves \( x=0, x=1, y=0 \) and \( y=f(x) \) is 4, then the maximum value of the function \( f \) is :", "image_url": ""}

{"text": "A cylindrical furnace has height ($H$) and diameter ($D$) both $1 \text{ m}$. It is maintained at temperature $360 \text{ K}$. The air gets heated inside the furnace at constant pressure $P_a$ and its temperature becomes $T = 360 \text{ K}$. The hot air with density $\rho$ rises up a vertical chimney of diameter $d = 0.1 \text{ m}$ and height $h = 9 \text{ m}$ above the furnace and exits the chimney. As a result, atmospheric air of density $\rho_a = 1.2 \text{ kg m}^{-3}$, pressure $P_a$ and temperature $T_a = 300 \text{ K}$ enters the furnace. Assume air as an ideal gas; neglect the variations in $\rho$ and $T$ inside the chimney and the furnace. Also ignore the viscous effects.

Considering the air flow to be streamline, the steady mass flow rate of air exiting the chimney is _________ $\text{gm s}^{-1}$.

[Given: The acceleration due to gravity $g = 10 \text{ m s}^{-2}$ and $\pi = 3.14$]", "image_url": "https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/d/1tOYXddaMHOW3iCmVwes8lJOldYgI9yeu=w1200"}

{"text": "A cylindrical furnace has height ($H$) and diameter ($D$) both $1 \text{ m}$. It is maintained at temperature $360 \text{ K}$. The air gets heated inside the furnace at constant pressure $P_a$ and its temperature becomes $T = 360 \text{ K}$. The hot air with density $\rho$ rises up a vertical chimney of diameter $d = 0.1 \text{ m}$ and height $h = 9 \text{ m}$ above the furnace and exits the chimney. As a result, atmospheric air of density $\rho_a = 1.2 \text{ kg m}^{-3}$, pressure $P_a$ and temperature $T_a = 300 \text{ K}$ enters the furnace. Assume air as an ideal gas; neglect the variations in $\rho$ and $T$ inside the chimney and the furnace. Also ignore the viscous effects.

When the chimney is closed using a cap at the top, a pressure difference $\Delta P$ develops between the top and the bottom surfaces of the cap. If the changes in the temperature and density of the hot air, due to the stoppage of air flow, are negligible, then the value of $\Delta P$ is __________ $N m^{-2}$.

[Given: The acceleration due to gravity $g = 10 \text{ m s}^{-2}$ and $\pi = 3.14$]", "image_url": "https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/d/1fHKlqTdTxJyp7aKJDMR1-OVrNDEMt95U=w1200"}

{"text": "Atoms of metals $\mathrm{x}, \mathrm{y}$, and $\mathrm{z}$ form face-centered cubic (fcc) unit cells with edge length $\mathrm{L}_{\mathrm{x}}$, body-centered cubic (bcc) unit cells with edge length $\mathrm{L}_y$, and simple cubic unit cells with edge length $\mathrm{L}_z$, respectively. If $\mathrm{r}_{\mathrm{z}}=\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \mathrm{r}_{\mathrm{y}} ; \mathrm{r}_{\mathrm{y}}=\frac{8}{\sqrt{3}} \mathrm{r}_{\mathrm{x}} ; M_{\mathrm{z}}=\frac{3}{2} M_{\mathrm{y}}$ and $M_{\mathrm{z}}=3 M_{\mathrm{x}}$, then the correct statement(s) is/are:

[Data: $M_x, M_y$, and $M_z$ are the molar masses of metals $\mathrm{x}, \mathrm{y}$, and $\mathrm{z}$.
$\mathrm{r}_{\mathrm{x}}, \mathrm{r}_{\mathrm{y}}$, and $\mathrm{r}_{\mathrm{z}}$ are the atomic radii of metals $\mathrm{x}, \mathrm{y}$, and $\mathrm{z}$.]", "image_url": ""}

{"text": "A trinitro compound, 1,3,5-tris-(4-nitrophenyl)benzene, on complete reaction with an excess of $Sn/HCl$ gives a major product, which on treatment with an excess of $NaNO_2/HCl$ at $0^\circ C$ provides $\mathbf{P}$ as the product. $\mathbf{P}$, upon treatment with excess of $H_2O$ at room temperature, gives the product $\mathbf{Q}$. Bromination of $\mathbf{Q}$ in aqueous medium furnishes the product $\mathbf{R}$. The compound $\mathbf{P}$ upon treatment with an excess of phenol under basic conditions gives the product $\mathbf{S}$. The molar mass difference between compounds $\mathbf{Q}$ and $\mathbf{R}$ is $474 \text{ g mol}^{-1}$ and between compounds $\mathbf{P}$ and $\mathbf{S}$ is $172.5 \text{ g mol}^{-1}$.

The number of heteroatoms present in one molecule of $\mathbf{R}$ is.

[all atoms apart from C and H are considered as heteroatom. (use : Molar Mass (in g $mol^{-1}$ H = 1, C = 12, N = 14,  O = 16, Br =80, Cl = 35.5]", "image_url": ""}

{"text": "Based on the VSEPR model, match the xenon compounds given in List-I with the corresponding geometries and the number of lone pairs on xenon given in List-II and choose the correct option.

$$\begin{array}{|l|l|} \hline \pmb{\text{List-I}} & \pmb{\text{List-II}} \\ \hline \text{(P) XeF}_2 & (1) \text{ Trigonal bipyramidal and two lone pair of electrons} \\ \hline \text{(Q) XeF}_4 & (2) \text{ Tetrahedral and one lone pair of electrons} \\ \hline \text{(R) XeO}_3 & (3) \text{ Octahedral and two lone pair of electrons} \\ \hline \text{(S) XeO}_3\text{F}_2 & (4) \text{ Trigonal bipyramidal and no lone pair of electrons} \\ \hline & (5) \text{ Trigonal bipyramidal and three lone pair of electrons} \\ \hline \end{array}$$
